WEBVTT

00:02.420 --> 00:04.378
(Wil Willis)
Since the dawn
of human civilization,

00:04.422 --> 00:07.423
mankind has made weapons.

00:07.466 --> 00:08.716
Whoa!

00:08.759 --> 00:10.259
(Willis)
Bladesmiths have honed

00:10.302 --> 00:13.053
and perfected their craft
over thousands of years

00:13.097 --> 00:14.972
and now for the first time ever,

00:15.016 --> 00:16.807
these men will go head-to-head

00:16.851 --> 00:19.101
and put their skills
to the ultimate test.

00:19.145 --> 00:21.103
Welcome to the forge.

00:21.147 --> 00:23.313
(Willis)
It starts with a lump
of raw steel

00:23.357 --> 00:24.648
and a ticking clock.

00:24.692 --> 00:26.358
And by the end of three rounds,

00:26.402 --> 00:27.860
the bladesmiths must deliver

00:27.903 --> 00:30.404
handmade weapons
that are works of art

00:30.448 --> 00:33.032
as well as deadly instruments
of war.

00:33.075 --> 00:36.118
These weapons must survive
explosive tests

00:36.162 --> 00:39.955
as well as the scrutiny of
an expert panel of judges.

00:39.999 --> 00:44.084
In the end, only one bladesmith
will take home $10,000

00:44.128 --> 00:47.004
and be crowned
a<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

00:47.048 --> 00:50.007
[epic rock music]

00:50.051 --> 00:52.885
♪ ♪

00:54.180 --> 00:57.681
[heavy rock music]

00:57.725 --> 00:58.891
(Matt)
My name's Matt Venier.

00:58.934 --> 01:00.601
If it's sharp or is on fire,

01:00.644 --> 01:02.061
I'm interested in it.

01:02.104 --> 01:03.771
(Gabriel)
My name is Gabriel Bell.

01:03.814 --> 01:06.398
I'm 30 years old and I like
Japanese sword making

01:06.442 --> 01:08.942
because I think it's the epitome
of refinement

01:08.986 --> 01:11.612
and technique of sword making.

01:11.655 --> 01:12.988
(Pete)
My name is Peter Burt.

01:13.032 --> 01:14.448
The first sword that I made

01:14.492 --> 01:16.200
I gave to my high school
girlfriend.

01:16.243 --> 01:19.203
She was not very excited
about it.

01:19.246 --> 01:20.788
(Dave)
I'm Dave Roeder.

01:20.831 --> 01:23.373
When I was 16, I followed
the sound of an anvil

01:23.417 --> 01:25.375
and I met a man
that was forging a knife.

01:25.419 --> 01:26.877
Got to watch it being done

01:26.921 --> 01:28.587
and I've been making knives
ever since.

01:28.631 --> 01:30.339
Gentlemen, welcome.

01:30.382 --> 01:32.800
Ahead of you
are three challenges

01:32.843 --> 01:35.886
designed to test just how good
you are in the forge.

01:35.930 --> 01:38.972
Each round pits you against
the clock and each other.

01:39.016 --> 01:42.851
When the time runs out, the
judges will examine your work.

01:42.895 --> 01:44.561
If it doesn't make the grade,

01:44.605 --> 01:47.314
you will be eliminated.

01:47.358 --> 01:48.315
Let's meet the judges.

01:48.359 --> 01:50.025
(Willis)
First up,

01:50.069 --> 01:52.653
solo weapons making expert
and internationally-knn

01:52.696 --> 01:55.280
master bladesmith J. Neilson.

01:55.324 --> 01:57.491
Next,
world-renowned swordsmith

01:57.535 --> 01:59.576
and rare weapons
re-creation specialist

01:59.620 --> 02:00.786
David Baker.

02:00.830 --> 02:02.830
And finally,
edged weapons specialist

02:02.873 --> 02:06.250
and martial artist
Doug Marcaida.

02:06.293 --> 02:07.709
It's time to make some blades.

02:07.753 --> 02:10.629
In front of you
on your anvil is a cloth.

02:10.673 --> 02:13.048
Go ahead and lift that up.

02:14.969 --> 02:17.886
That is a block of W2.

02:17.930 --> 02:20.180
High carbon forging steel.

02:20.224 --> 02:22.766
From that lump of raw metal

02:22.810 --> 02:26.895
you must design and forge
a blade of your choice.

02:26.939 --> 02:28.981
You have ten minutes
to design the blade

02:29.024 --> 02:32.568
and you will have three hours
to forge the blade.

02:32.611 --> 02:35.904
The blade has to be
at least 12 inches in length,

02:35.948 --> 02:38.031
but not more than 14 inches.

02:38.075 --> 02:42.077
You must also set a hamon line.

02:42.121 --> 02:43.787
(Gabriel)
For someone who's trained

02:43.831 --> 02:45.247
as a Japanese swordsmith,

02:45.291 --> 02:47.916
making a hamon is just
a everyday thing.

02:47.960 --> 02:50.377
So it's not any big challenge
for me.

02:50.421 --> 02:53.046
Remember,
after three hours,

02:53.090 --> 02:55.215
one of you will be eliminated

02:55.259 --> 02:57.301
and asked to surrender
your weapon.

02:57.344 --> 03:00.220
Your ten-minute design window
begins...

03:00.264 --> 03:01.138
Now.

03:01.182 --> 03:04.224
[percussive music]

03:04.268 --> 03:05.517
♪ ♪

03:05.561 --> 03:07.102
(Dave)
So I chose the bowie knife.

03:07.146 --> 03:09.313
It's used for hunting

03:09.356 --> 03:10.981
and, in some cases,
defense.

03:11.025 --> 03:12.900
I've made hundreds of them.

03:12.943 --> 03:14.818
I can make this thing
blindfolded.

03:14.862 --> 03:17.070
(Pete)
The knife that I designed

03:17.114 --> 03:19.448
is part kukri,
part bowie.

03:19.491 --> 03:21.200
Both were fighting knives

03:21.243 --> 03:22.659
that were famous in history.

03:22.703 --> 03:24.536
If I'm known for anything,

03:24.580 --> 03:26.914
it's for not making
straight blades.

03:26.957 --> 03:28.749
I don't make
conventional swords.

03:28.792 --> 03:31.960
I almost always make Persian
or African-inspired,

03:32.004 --> 03:35.422
very curvy knives
and swords.

03:35.466 --> 03:37.466
(Gabriel)
I'm making a Japanese
short sword

03:37.509 --> 03:39.176
known as a wakizashi.

03:39.220 --> 03:40.886
I've chose to make a wakizashi

03:40.930 --> 03:43.513
because it's a time-tested
weapon

03:43.557 --> 03:46.850
that has been used by samurai
for hundreds of years,

03:46.894 --> 03:48.101
and I would say my work
certainly reflects

03:48.145 --> 03:51.230
the Japanese aesthetic.

03:51.273 --> 03:53.398
I'm second-generation
swordsmith,

03:53.442 --> 03:56.401
so I'd say the stakes
are somewhat high for me.

03:56.445 --> 03:58.362
I have a lot to prove.

03:58.405 --> 04:00.405
(Matt)
I'm designing a hybrid

04:00.449 --> 04:04.159
tanto/bowie-esque kind of blade.

04:04.203 --> 04:05.786
My style of blade-making is,

04:05.829 --> 04:08.497
I tend to prefer
the Japanese-style blade.

04:08.540 --> 04:12.417
My strategy in the design phase
is to come up with something

04:12.461 --> 04:16.713
that takes some of the
Japanese-inspired work that I do

04:16.757 --> 04:18.340
but change it up a little bit

04:18.384 --> 04:21.093
so it's not the same
as everyone else's.

04:21.136 --> 04:24.221
Gentlemen, your design window
is now closed.

04:24.265 --> 04:26.848
You may begin forging
your blades...

04:26.892 --> 04:27.849
Now.

04:27.893 --> 04:30.852
[heavy rock music]

04:30.896 --> 04:33.855
♪ ♪

04:33.899 --> 04:37.317
Okay, we got one-- two so far,
with steel in the oven.

04:37.361 --> 04:39.403
(Neilson)
Matt just went to get
a bar of steel.

04:39.446 --> 04:44.032
I think he's gonna go weld
a handle onto his block.

04:44.076 --> 04:45.659
(Matt)
I rush over to the welder

04:45.703 --> 04:47.202
'cause I don't like
to use tongs.

04:47.246 --> 04:49.037
You're always fiddling
with them.

04:49.081 --> 04:51.081
They never quite fit
exactly the way I want.

04:51.125 --> 04:54.418
As I'm welding, everyone else
has their piece of metal

04:54.461 --> 04:56.461
in their forge
and it's starting to heat up,

04:56.505 --> 04:59.756
and I know I'm a little bit
behind at this point.

04:59.800 --> 05:02.009
(Gabriel)
The time limit is definitely
my biggest concern.

05:02.052 --> 05:03.760
I think it's
the biggest challenge.

05:03.804 --> 05:07.055
I've never done a blade,
start to finish, in three hours.

05:07.099 --> 05:10.976
So I'm very concerned
about that.

05:11.020 --> 05:13.020
'Cause I'm starting with
this lump of steel.

05:13.063 --> 05:14.896
I got to draw it out,
so it's really critical.

05:14.940 --> 05:16.523
I can't move on
to the next stage

05:16.567 --> 05:19.151
until I've got the length
that I need.

05:19.194 --> 05:22.237
Right now, I'm really
appreciating the process

05:22.281 --> 05:23.739
of creating the weapon.

05:23.782 --> 05:25.824
The blade is very much,
in many cultures,

05:25.868 --> 05:27.326
something that's
very spiritual,

05:27.369 --> 05:29.703
and to see
the forging process,

05:29.747 --> 05:31.246
you know, putting
their power into it,

05:31.290 --> 05:33.290
I mean, that to me
is fascinating.

05:33.334 --> 05:36.960
♪ ♪

05:37.004 --> 05:39.129
(Neilson)
All right,
we've got a piece of steel out.

05:39.173 --> 05:40.839
(Dave)
I have no concerns.

05:40.883 --> 05:42.966
When I'm working in the shop,
I have no concerns.

05:43.010 --> 05:44.384
I zone out the world.

05:44.428 --> 05:46.011
I have to get it done.

05:46.055 --> 05:49.306
Oh!
This is so nice.

05:49.350 --> 05:51.308
(Neilson)
Dave needs to get a little bit
hotter, I think.

05:51.352 --> 05:53.643
(Willis)
Would you say that he pulled
that out a little bit early?

05:53.687 --> 05:55.062
Little early.

05:55.105 --> 05:56.646
(Neilson)
You want the steel hotter.

05:56.690 --> 05:59.524
You could put fine
stress fractures into the steel

05:59.568 --> 06:01.276
you'll never see,

06:01.320 --> 06:02.944
but they'll show up when
your tip of your blade breaks

06:02.988 --> 06:03.945
later on.

06:03.989 --> 06:06.948
[rock music]

06:06.992 --> 06:08.283
♪ ♪

06:08.327 --> 06:09.743
(Pete)
I think what sets me apart

06:09.787 --> 06:11.995
from the other competitors is,

06:12.039 --> 06:14.748
they are all actually
full-time knife makers.

06:14.792 --> 06:17.667
and I split my time
between knife making

06:17.711 --> 06:19.336
and ornamental ironwork.

06:19.380 --> 06:22.422
I feel that the ornamental
ironwork actually brings

06:22.466 --> 06:26.468
a different perspective
to working with knives.

06:26.512 --> 06:28.011
If I win the competition,

06:28.055 --> 06:30.639
I will have exceeded
my own expectations

06:30.682 --> 06:35.268
and me and my wife will go
to Hawaii.

06:35.312 --> 06:38.313
(Willis)
Gentlemen, two hours to go.

06:38.357 --> 06:40.065
[heavy rock music]

06:40.109 --> 06:41.608
Oh, we got Matt going
to the hammer.

06:41.652 --> 06:43.235
Gonna see here,
you'll see the difference

06:43.278 --> 06:45.070
with a stick welded
on there.

06:45.114 --> 06:46.279
Much more secure grip.

06:46.323 --> 06:47.656
(Neilson)
See, this is where

06:47.699 --> 06:49.241
he might be able to
make up some time.

06:49.284 --> 06:50.742
(Matt)
I'm very worried
about being behind

06:50.786 --> 06:52.661
There's limited amount of time

06:52.704 --> 06:55.038
and every step is crucial.

06:55.082 --> 06:58.083
(Willis)
Oh, we've got some steel
on the floor.

06:58.127 --> 07:01.086
Gentlemen, you have
90 minutes remaining.

07:01.130 --> 07:03.422
(Baker)
Dave's over here straightening
his blade.

07:03.465 --> 07:04.464
He's gonna go to the grinder
in a minute.

07:04.508 --> 07:05.465
(Neilson)
Oh, yeah.

07:05.509 --> 07:06.758
Dave's doing a good job.

07:06.802 --> 07:08.677
(Dave)
Skills that help me the most

07:08.720 --> 07:11.555
is the ability to be able
to forge proficiently

07:11.598 --> 07:14.433
and then also grinding.

07:14.476 --> 07:16.184
So I can grind it real quick

07:16.228 --> 07:17.811
and get the job done right
the first time.

07:17.855 --> 07:19.604
[chuckles]

07:19.648 --> 07:21.648
When my daughter turned five,

07:21.692 --> 07:23.567
I made her a rapier sword.

07:23.610 --> 07:25.360
Not everybody that age
gets a sword.

07:25.404 --> 07:27.696
And it was taller than her,
so it was kind of cute.

07:27.739 --> 07:29.573
(Dave)
I love it.

07:30.868 --> 07:32.159
(Pete)
Usually, in my own shop,

07:32.202 --> 07:34.202
I would be setting
this blade aside

07:34.246 --> 07:37.330
to cool slowly before grinding,

07:37.374 --> 07:38.999
but I don't have
that luxury now.

07:39.042 --> 07:40.876
I have to cool it off
very quickly

07:40.919 --> 07:43.336
so I'm swinging it around
like a madman.

07:43.380 --> 07:47.132
(Dave)
Beau-ti-ful.

07:47.176 --> 07:48.550
[chuckles]

07:48.594 --> 07:50.677
You destroyed it.
That was great.

07:50.721 --> 07:54.431
Got to get the job done,
right?

07:54.475 --> 07:56.099
(Willis)
When does the hamon line go on?

07:56.143 --> 07:57.684
Before or after
the quenching process?

07:57.728 --> 07:59.144
During the quenching process.

07:59.188 --> 08:01.229
Put the clay on before
it goes in the oil.

08:01.273 --> 08:02.314
Okay.

08:02.357 --> 08:03.356
And the hamon actually sets

08:03.400 --> 08:04.483
during the hardening process.

08:04.526 --> 08:06.401
Okay.

08:06.445 --> 08:07.777
(Gabriel)
For someone who's trained

08:07.821 --> 08:09.279
as a Japanese swordsmith,

08:09.323 --> 08:13.033
making a hamon is really
just a piece of cake.

08:13.076 --> 08:15.202
Once the blade's up to
the right temperature,

08:15.245 --> 08:18.622
I quickly pull it out,
quench it in the oil.

08:18.665 --> 08:19.998
That's where the excitement is.

08:20.042 --> 08:23.001
[heavy rock music]

08:23.045 --> 08:28.548
♪ ♪

08:28.592 --> 08:31.384
The last 30 minutes are just
a race against the clock

08:31.428 --> 08:34.095
to grind this thick edge down
to a sharp blade.

08:34.139 --> 08:37.766
♪ ♪

08:37.809 --> 08:40.685
(Baker)
Yeah, he's in. Matt's in.

08:40.729 --> 08:43.855
(Matt)
Well, all right. Happy days.

08:43.899 --> 08:47.442
♪ ♪

08:47.486 --> 08:50.403
(Pete)
I feel really great about
the hamon I'm doing.

08:50.447 --> 08:53.114
I've got plenty of time left
to finish out the blade.

08:53.158 --> 08:54.574
I feel pretty confident.

08:54.618 --> 08:57.118
How thick is that clay
supposed to be on there?

08:57.162 --> 08:58.912
Does it matter?
Does it have an effect?

08:58.956 --> 09:01.164
It depends on what
you're trying to do.

09:01.208 --> 09:03.917
The thickness you put it on,
the way you put it on

09:03.961 --> 09:06.878
will bring out different
patterns in your hamon.

09:08.799 --> 09:10.840
- There he goes, he's--
- There we go.

09:10.884 --> 09:12.259
(Neilson)
Yeah, he needs to move it
around.

09:12.302 --> 09:13.343
(Baker)
There it is.

09:13.387 --> 09:15.470
He's stirring a little bit.

09:15.514 --> 09:18.765
Based on how this looks,
I should have a good hamon.

09:18.809 --> 09:19.891
We'll find out.

09:19.935 --> 09:27.065
♪ ♪

09:27.109 --> 09:30.318
(Dave)
I have to add a temporal line
or a hamon in this thing.

09:30.362 --> 09:31.987
I've never worked with this
specific steel before

09:32.030 --> 09:34.239
so I don't know
if it's gonna work.

09:34.283 --> 09:36.408
My heart's pounding
like that power hammer.

09:36.451 --> 09:40.745
The pressure's on
and I need to get it done.

09:40.789 --> 09:42.289
(Neilson)
Now we got a big problem.

09:42.332 --> 09:44.499
He went ahead and quenched it.

09:44.543 --> 09:47.252
He didn't put clay on it.

09:47.296 --> 09:49.379
- He's not gonna have a hamon.
- Nope.

09:49.423 --> 09:51.840
♪ ♪

09:57.639 --> 10:00.599
[rock music]

10:00.642 --> 10:02.225
♪ ♪

10:02.269 --> 10:04.436
(Dave)
I have to add a hamon
in this thing.

10:04.479 --> 10:06.396
I've never worked with this
specific steel before,

10:06.440 --> 10:07.939
so I don't know
if it's gonna work.

10:07.983 --> 10:09.399
(Willis)
Oh, we've got some fire
over here.

10:09.443 --> 10:10.400
(Neilson)
Now we got a big problem.

10:10.444 --> 10:12.360
Now we have a big problem.

10:12.404 --> 10:14.279
- We've got a blade on fire.
- He didn't put clay on it.

10:14.323 --> 10:16.323
- He's not gonna have a hamon.
- Nope.

10:16.366 --> 10:17.365
Oh, man.

10:17.409 --> 10:18.700
So what are we
looking at here?

10:18.744 --> 10:19.909
(Neilson)
The blade's hard now.

10:19.953 --> 10:21.661
(Dave)
I can use clay,

10:21.705 --> 10:23.413
but the way I've always done it
in the past

10:23.457 --> 10:27.375
is the old way--
no clay, just do it.

10:27.419 --> 10:29.544
Oh, he's quenched it again.

10:29.588 --> 10:31.630
- He's done a second quench.
- There it is again.

10:31.673 --> 10:33.923
(Neilson)
He's doing a multi-quench.

10:33.967 --> 10:36.301
As long as I heat my edge,
it gets hot,

10:36.345 --> 10:38.261
the spine doesn't,
when it goes into the oil,

10:38.305 --> 10:40.972
that edge is gonna get hard,
the spine won't.

10:41.016 --> 10:42.891
That's gonna give me
my hamon line.

10:42.934 --> 10:44.351
I got to give him credit.

10:44.394 --> 10:46.186
That's a pretty bold move

10:46.229 --> 10:48.188
for a competition like this.

10:48.231 --> 10:49.606
(Willis)
So he decided

10:49.650 --> 10:51.524
to try to do
the hamon line without clay?

10:51.568 --> 10:52.567
(Neilson)
Yeah.

10:52.611 --> 10:53.777
He had a plan,

10:53.820 --> 10:55.195
and whether it worked out
or not,

10:55.238 --> 10:57.364
we'll see.

10:57.407 --> 10:58.990
Final minute, gentlemen.

10:59.034 --> 11:01.993
[dramatic music]

11:02.037 --> 11:08.124
♪ ♪

11:08.168 --> 11:10.210
(Willis)
Ten, nine,

11:10.253 --> 11:12.295
eight, seven,

11:12.339 --> 11:14.381
six, five,

11:14.424 --> 11:16.132
four, three,

11:16.176 --> 11:17.842
two, one.

11:17.886 --> 11:19.719
Time is up, gentlemen.

11:19.763 --> 11:22.013
Stop what you're doing.

11:22.057 --> 11:23.098
(Gabriel)
Time's up.

11:23.141 --> 11:25.058
I've taken a lump of steel

11:25.102 --> 11:28.144
and made it into a wakizashi
in three hours.

11:28.188 --> 11:30.647
I don't think my dad
could be prouder.

11:30.691 --> 11:32.399
(Willis)
Gentlemen,

11:32.442 --> 11:36.528
your challenge was to produce a
blade between 12 and 14 inches.

11:36.571 --> 11:38.029
Additionally,

11:38.073 --> 11:41.574
your blade must have included
a hamon line.

11:41.618 --> 11:44.536
But now it's time for the judges
to take a look at your work.

11:44.579 --> 11:48.289
Matt, please present your blade
to the judges.

11:48.333 --> 11:51.292
[rock music]

11:51.336 --> 11:52.752
♪ ♪

11:52.796 --> 11:53.920
It's got a nice
overall look to it.

11:53.964 --> 11:55.505
I like the hamon,

11:55.549 --> 11:57.340
came out nice and clear.

11:57.384 --> 11:58.800
(Matt)
Thank you.

11:58.844 --> 12:00.093
When you were designing this,

12:00.137 --> 12:01.886
you had a lot wider blade.

12:01.930 --> 12:03.388
I'm used to a much bigger anvil,

12:03.432 --> 12:06.224
so it was much harder work
getting it to move

12:06.268 --> 12:07.726
the way I wanted it to.

12:07.769 --> 12:09.811
Gabriel, you're up next.

12:09.855 --> 12:14.232
♪ ♪

12:14.276 --> 12:15.817
(Willis)
Doug?

12:15.861 --> 12:18.611
I appreciate-- I can see
the Asian influence on this.

12:18.655 --> 12:21.823
It was kind of cool to see
the way you brought the passion.

12:21.867 --> 12:24.534
It's got a lot of meat
in it still.

12:24.578 --> 12:25.827
We had a lot of metal
to work with there.

12:25.871 --> 12:27.829
Yeah, there was a lot
of metal there.

12:27.873 --> 12:29.414
(Baker)
Do you feel like you maybe

12:29.458 --> 12:31.499
jumped to the anvil
a little soon?

12:31.543 --> 12:33.793
I feel like a little more time
on the hydraulic press

12:33.837 --> 12:36.713
might have saved myself
a little time on the forging.

12:36.757 --> 12:38.882
(Neilson)
I'm having trouble
with the hamon line.

12:38.925 --> 12:42.927
What I can see of it
is really pretty low.

12:42.971 --> 12:44.804
I wish you'd been able
to clean it up a little more

12:44.848 --> 12:46.222
and get it in some acid

12:46.266 --> 12:48.683
so I can really see
what was going on there.

12:48.727 --> 12:50.727
Pete, you're up next.

12:50.771 --> 12:55.732
♪ ♪

12:55.776 --> 12:57.609
I like the design.

12:57.652 --> 13:00.987
A little more fantasy-inspired,
I'm assuming, than traditional,

13:01.031 --> 13:02.822
but it's got some nice curves
to it.

13:02.866 --> 13:05.241
The line came out nice.

13:05.285 --> 13:06.951
It's one of the most
distinguished hamon lines

13:06.995 --> 13:08.828
I've seen today.

13:08.872 --> 13:10.705
The tang--

13:10.749 --> 13:12.707
it's definitely
gonna be a problem.

13:12.751 --> 13:14.292
With the blade
being so heavy,

13:14.336 --> 13:17.629
such a small tang
can affect the balance.

13:17.672 --> 13:19.923
Balance is very important.

13:19.966 --> 13:21.424
The ability to be able
to recuperate

13:21.468 --> 13:24.844
and not feel
it's just a chopper.

13:24.888 --> 13:26.679
Dave, step up, please.

13:26.723 --> 13:31.684
♪ ♪

13:31.728 --> 13:35.396
Everything looks nice
and straight.

13:35.440 --> 13:36.940
I got to ask, though.

13:36.983 --> 13:38.566
You didn't go near the clay.

13:38.610 --> 13:40.777
Well, I've made knives
as long as I have

13:40.821 --> 13:43.112
and not once
have I ever used clay.

13:43.156 --> 13:46.616
I mean, the line is there.
It's a little...

13:46.660 --> 13:50.870
Blah, but overall,
it's a very nice blade.

13:50.914 --> 13:52.247
Good.
Thank you.

13:52.290 --> 13:54.082
You were calm and cool
all throughout,

13:54.125 --> 13:56.000
so how much of that
was strategy?

13:56.044 --> 13:59.045
Well, not to sound
egotistical, but...

13:59.089 --> 14:00.755
[laughs]

14:00.799 --> 14:02.340
(Dave)
It's just what I do.

14:02.384 --> 14:03.925
I...

14:03.969 --> 14:05.343
Get the job done.

14:05.387 --> 14:07.178
Very cool.
Thank you.

14:07.222 --> 14:08.346
(Willis)
Gentlemen,

14:08.390 --> 14:09.973
this is gonna be a tough call.

14:10.016 --> 14:12.267
The judges will take some time
to make their decision.

14:12.310 --> 14:15.270
♪ ♪

14:15.313 --> 14:16.896
That was pretty intense.

14:16.940 --> 14:18.773
I couldn't imagine
getting that much done

14:18.817 --> 14:21.192
in that short amount
of time.

14:21.236 --> 14:22.527
(Gabriel)
That was rough.

14:22.571 --> 14:23.653
That was fun.

14:23.697 --> 14:25.321
- [chuckles]
- I liked that.

14:25.365 --> 14:27.866
So let's go ahead and start
with Dave's blade there.

14:27.909 --> 14:29.701
(Willis)
Look at the criteria.

14:29.744 --> 14:31.536
- Does he have a hamon line?
- Yeah.

14:31.580 --> 14:32.537
(Baker)
The clay's gonna pretty much

14:32.581 --> 14:34.080
guarantee you have a hamon.

14:34.124 --> 14:35.915
Not going with the clay,
it's a shot in the dark.

14:35.959 --> 14:36.916
You don't know where
it's gonna be.

14:36.960 --> 14:38.251
- Yeah.
- Exactly.

14:38.295 --> 14:39.586
- Yeah, they--
- Is that yours, Gabe?

14:39.629 --> 14:41.296
(Dave)
They picked mine up first.

14:41.339 --> 14:43.006
Looking at this blade,
we're looking at something

14:43.049 --> 14:46.217
that's near-- you know,
finishing quality.

14:46.261 --> 14:49.971
- So he's ahead of the curve.
- Right. Okay.

14:50.015 --> 14:52.640
Let's take a look
at Gabe's blade.

14:52.684 --> 14:56.561
(Neilson)
I mean, I like the
overall concept.

14:56.605 --> 14:58.980
- Hamon line?
- It's hard to see any.

14:59.024 --> 15:01.024
I mean, there is some,
but it's so low.

15:01.067 --> 15:04.235
And if you do not have
a hard edge all the way up,

15:04.279 --> 15:07.280
then it's not
a functioning weapon.

15:07.324 --> 15:09.365
(Gabriel)
What are they saying?

15:09.409 --> 15:11.034
(Willis)
Let's move on to Matt's blade.

15:11.077 --> 15:12.952
(Neilson)
Matt, he's got a hamon,

15:12.996 --> 15:14.913
even without etching it
in the acid,

15:14.956 --> 15:16.122
you can still see it
very clearly.

15:16.166 --> 15:17.540
(Willis)
Yeah, okay.

15:17.584 --> 15:20.043
The other thing that
we kind of noticed--

15:20.086 --> 15:21.961
where the plunge line starts.

15:22.005 --> 15:24.005
(Neilson)
The plunge line is

15:24.049 --> 15:26.382
where the blade edge
drops down

15:26.426 --> 15:28.468
and comes to the center
of your edge.

15:28.511 --> 15:30.219
- Oh, no.
- Right here.

15:30.263 --> 15:31.804
(Willis)
I see exactly what
you're talking about.

15:31.848 --> 15:32.972
Wow.

15:33.016 --> 15:35.391
His aren't symmetrical at all.

15:35.435 --> 15:37.644
Sometimes the steel does
what it wants to do.

15:37.687 --> 15:38.853
- You know?
- It does.

15:38.897 --> 15:40.563
(Matt)
I'm not in full control.

15:40.607 --> 15:42.398
There's a little bit of magic
in there somewhere.

15:42.442 --> 15:43.858
What about Pete's blade?

15:43.902 --> 15:45.485
(Marcaida)
It's very sexy.

15:45.528 --> 15:48.279
People also pick up a blade
based on its looks.

15:48.323 --> 15:51.532
So we have to look at the
aesthetics as much as function.

15:51.576 --> 15:53.576
There's also what
appeals to you.

15:53.620 --> 15:55.411
I have a big issue
with the tang, though.

15:55.455 --> 15:56.996
Why does the tang
worry you?

15:57.040 --> 15:58.748
Would it break
in the testing?

15:58.792 --> 16:00.833
Well, a lot of your stress
on a hidden tang knife

16:00.877 --> 16:03.127
is gonna be here,
right here, at that joint.

16:03.171 --> 16:04.253
And you want a lot of meat.

16:04.297 --> 16:05.922
You want a strong section there.

16:05.966 --> 16:09.467
And having the tang this thin
just worries me.

16:09.511 --> 16:11.928
(Willis)
Okay, so we have four blades.

16:11.972 --> 16:15.932
Do we know which contestant
we're gonna eliminate?

16:15.976 --> 16:17.058
- Yes.
- Yeah.

16:17.102 --> 16:18.226
- Yes, we do.
- All right.

16:18.269 --> 16:19.310
Let's go ahead
and let them know.

16:19.354 --> 16:22.313
[tense music]

16:22.357 --> 16:25.024
♪ ♪

16:25.068 --> 16:26.401
(Gabriel)
It's important for me to make it

16:26.444 --> 16:28.236
to the next round
of this competition

16:28.279 --> 16:31.948
because I have my father and his
teacher's lineage to represent.

16:31.992 --> 16:34.283
(Dave)
So I'm hoping that the judges
will be able to recognize

16:34.327 --> 16:37.370
that with this particular piece,
the beauty in my work

16:37.414 --> 16:38.955
is in its simplicity.

16:38.999 --> 16:42.041
Otherwise, this is gonna be
my ticket home.

16:42.085 --> 16:46.671
♪ ♪

16:46.715 --> 16:48.172
(Willis)
Gentlemen,

16:48.216 --> 16:50.216
the judges have made
their decision.

16:50.260 --> 16:54.220
♪ ♪

16:54.264 --> 16:56.973
Gabriel,

16:57.017 --> 17:00.768
you didn't make the cut.

17:00.812 --> 17:02.687
Gabriel,
we really appreciate the work

17:02.731 --> 17:03.938
you put into your knife.

17:03.982 --> 17:05.440
It was the hamon line.

17:05.483 --> 17:06.691
We could only see it

17:06.735 --> 17:08.943
in one or two small sections
of the blade

17:08.987 --> 17:11.154
and it was extremely close
to the edge.

17:11.197 --> 17:13.906
And if we can't see
that hamon,

17:13.950 --> 17:15.908
we can't tell if
that whole edge is hard,

17:15.952 --> 17:18.870
and if that whole edge
isn't hard, it's not a weapon.

17:18.913 --> 17:22.206
Thank you for the opportunity
to partake in this competition.

17:22.250 --> 17:23.875
Gabriel,

17:23.918 --> 17:26.044
please surrender your weapon.

17:29.841 --> 17:31.382
I think my hamon
may have been

17:31.426 --> 17:33.468
a little too subtle
for the judges' taste.

17:33.511 --> 17:35.553
Maybe the Japanese aesthetic
kind of got the better of me

17:35.597 --> 17:37.138
on this one.

17:37.182 --> 17:38.973
I really would like to move on
to the next round,

17:39.017 --> 17:40.767
but after those judges'
comments,

17:40.810 --> 17:43.770
my confidence has taken
a little bit of a blow, I'd say.

17:43.813 --> 17:47.482
♪ ♪

17:47.525 --> 17:50.735
[dramatic music]

17:50.779 --> 17:52.945
Gentlemen, congratulations.

17:52.989 --> 17:54.280
You've all forged your blades

17:54.324 --> 17:55.948
but your work here
is far from over.

17:55.992 --> 17:58.743
Your second challenge will be
to complete your work

17:58.787 --> 18:01.662
by turning it into
a fully functioning weapon.

18:01.706 --> 18:04.165
You must design and craft
a handle

18:04.209 --> 18:07.043
out of the materials
provided for you.

18:07.087 --> 18:09.378
Also, you can use that time

18:09.422 --> 18:11.547
to address any mistakes you made
in round one.

18:11.591 --> 18:13.257
When the time runs out,

18:13.301 --> 18:15.968
each blade will be tested
on its strength

18:16.012 --> 18:18.513
and durability in a wood chop.

18:18.556 --> 18:21.474
We will also see how well
it holds an edge

18:21.518 --> 18:23.935
in a specially-designed
sharpness test.

18:23.978 --> 18:26.729
Your blades will be judged
on design,

18:26.773 --> 18:30.024
form, and how well it performs
in these tests.

18:30.068 --> 18:31.692
At the end of this challenge,

18:31.736 --> 18:35.154
one of you will be eliminated.

18:35.198 --> 18:36.906
There are three hours
on the clock.

18:36.950 --> 18:39.951
Your time starts...

18:39.994 --> 18:40.952
Now.

18:40.995 --> 18:43.955
[dramatic percussive music]

18:43.998 --> 18:45.665
♪ ♪

18:45.708 --> 18:47.667
(Matt) It's important to have
a good solid handle.

18:47.710 --> 18:50.628
It's the interface between
the user and the knife.

18:50.672 --> 18:52.171
The shape's important.

18:52.215 --> 18:54.132
What it's made out of
is important.

18:54.175 --> 18:57.093
I know the judges are gonna
look at the plunges

18:57.137 --> 18:59.303
and make sure they're as even
as possible.

18:59.347 --> 19:02.765
So I need to fix this before
I start with anything else.

19:02.809 --> 19:06.519
[rock music]

19:06.563 --> 19:11.065
I have a lot more material out
towards the tip of this blade.

19:11.109 --> 19:14.986
So I need more weight
in the handle to balance that,

19:15.029 --> 19:17.530
or else, this will feel
really front-heavy.

19:17.574 --> 19:19.323
Pete looks like
he's using brass.

19:19.367 --> 19:21.534
Exactly, 'cause he said
because the blade's heavy,

19:21.578 --> 19:24.579
I'm gonna counterbalance it
with brass.

19:24.622 --> 19:27.915
Fitting up curvy fittings is
much more of a pain in the ass.

19:27.959 --> 19:30.418
Now I need to fit everything
to this curve.

19:32.463 --> 19:34.755
I've fixed the plunges
as best as I can.

19:34.799 --> 19:38.009
Now I need to move on to fitting
the wood to the tang.

19:41.097 --> 19:43.556
So I burned the handle on.

19:43.600 --> 19:45.308
This is something I never do.

19:45.351 --> 19:47.435
Now what's the danger of
affecting the metal with that?

19:47.478 --> 19:49.687
You could overheat it.

19:49.731 --> 19:51.772
This could blow up in my face

19:51.816 --> 19:53.191
and I could wreck
this piece of wood

19:53.234 --> 19:54.525
and then I'm starting
from scratch.

19:54.569 --> 19:57.528
[dramatic music]

19:57.572 --> 19:59.238
♪ ♪

20:04.871 --> 20:06.996
(Matt)
Now I need to move on to fitting

20:07.040 --> 20:09.248
the wood to the tang.

20:09.292 --> 20:11.667
So I burned the handle on.

20:11.711 --> 20:13.336
I'm very nervous.

20:13.379 --> 20:15.046
This could end things
right here.

20:15.089 --> 20:17.715
I don't know if I can recover
if this goes wrong.

20:19.510 --> 20:22.929
I slowly build up some heat
on the tip of the tang

20:22.972 --> 20:26.140
and I slide the wood on...

20:26.184 --> 20:28.309
And it fits perfectly.

20:28.353 --> 20:30.478
(Matt)
Now we're cooking with gas.

20:30.521 --> 20:32.355
♪ ♪

20:32.398 --> 20:34.023
It's really important to select
the right handle material

20:34.067 --> 20:35.191
for the piece.

20:35.235 --> 20:37.568
If I don't have the right look

20:37.612 --> 20:39.862
between the handle
and the blade,

20:39.906 --> 20:43.115
it's not gonna look
proportionally right.

20:43.159 --> 20:44.283
(Baker)
Dave's handle,

20:44.327 --> 20:45.618
it's a real simple design.

20:45.662 --> 20:47.203
Yeah, so you know,

20:47.247 --> 20:49.872
Dave's got the best shot
at moving forward quickly.

20:49.916 --> 20:51.415
♪ ♪

20:51.459 --> 20:52.667
(Willis) Is that a good way
to break the bit?

20:52.710 --> 20:54.502
(Neilson)
Oh, yeah.

20:54.545 --> 20:55.962
- I think the chip's loose.
- Well, it's gonna be.

20:56.005 --> 20:57.797
♪ ♪

20:57.840 --> 21:01.300
(Dave)
I do have my own unusual way
of doing things.

21:01.344 --> 21:05.930
It's just the way I do it.

21:05.974 --> 21:08.099
I'll do my fittings first.

21:08.142 --> 21:09.892
Once I get that done and shaped,

21:09.936 --> 21:11.352
I'll move on to my handle.

21:11.396 --> 21:15.856
♪ ♪

21:15.900 --> 21:18.109
I like it.

21:18.152 --> 21:21.320
[heavy rock music]

21:21.364 --> 21:23.197
(Neilson)
Pete is burning
the wood on also,

21:23.241 --> 21:26.742
like Matt did, except he's doing
it a little faster with a torch.

21:26.786 --> 21:28.911
If burning the tang in
doesn't go quickly,

21:28.955 --> 21:31.163
this could be bad news for me.

21:31.207 --> 21:33.874
(Willis)
You have one hour remaining.

21:33.918 --> 21:38.170
♪ ♪

21:38.214 --> 21:41.257
(Neilson)
Dave looks happy with his fit.

21:41.301 --> 21:48.347
♪ ♪

21:48.391 --> 21:49.390
(Neilson)
Now what's he doing?

21:49.434 --> 21:51.225
He's pulling a perichord.

21:51.269 --> 21:52.727
(Baker)
Oh, he's doing a wrap
over the whole thing.

21:52.770 --> 21:54.437
He's gonna do a wrap.

21:54.480 --> 21:55.813
He's using the Micarta
as an endcap for his wrap.

21:55.857 --> 21:57.148
To hold in place.

21:57.191 --> 21:58.691
So he is gonna do
a wrapped handle.

21:58.735 --> 22:01.193
I came to bladesmithing
through an art background.

22:01.237 --> 22:05.281
I transitioned from painting
motorcycles to bladesmithing

22:05.325 --> 22:09.994
because bladesmithing is
a much deeper form of art to me.

22:10.038 --> 22:11.746
That might look really nice.

22:11.789 --> 22:14.040
(Matt)
And I want to use
my Japanese influence

22:14.083 --> 22:15.875
to make this Japanese handle

22:15.918 --> 22:19.045
because it's so different from
everybody else's knife.

22:19.088 --> 22:20.963
(Matt)
Oh, my hands are cramping.

22:21.007 --> 22:23.174
Why do I do this to myself?

22:23.217 --> 22:25.217
♪ ♪

22:25.261 --> 22:27.053
(Dave)
So I decided
not to pin my blade,

22:27.096 --> 22:30.014
but the epoxy that I'm using
for this...

22:30.058 --> 22:31.432
Down she goes.

22:31.476 --> 22:32.725
Is pretty damn strong.

22:32.769 --> 22:34.352
♪ ♪

22:34.395 --> 22:37.104
What worries me is,
he's gonna count on epoxy

22:37.148 --> 22:38.522
to hold it together.

22:38.566 --> 22:41.025
(Baker)
I can't imagine that he would,

22:41.069 --> 22:44.278
but it's not unheard of.

22:44.322 --> 22:45.988
(Dave)
I'm not gonna have an issue
with this.

22:46.032 --> 22:46.989
Whoa.

22:47.033 --> 22:48.866
[dramatic music]

22:48.910 --> 22:52.119
(Willis)
You have ten seconds remaining.

22:52.163 --> 22:54.080
Five, four,

22:54.123 --> 22:56.957
three, two,
one.

22:57.001 --> 23:00.044
(Willis)
Blades down.

23:00.088 --> 23:02.922
Looking around,
I immediately see some things

23:02.965 --> 23:05.341
about both the knives
that I'm not sure about,

23:05.385 --> 23:08.386
but I see things about my knife
that I'm not sure about.

23:08.429 --> 23:10.262
How that's gonna stack up
with the judges,

23:10.306 --> 23:12.640
I really can't tell.

23:12.683 --> 23:14.433
(Willis)
Okay, gentlemen,

23:14.477 --> 23:17.978
it's time to see what your
blades are really capable of.

23:18.022 --> 23:20.940
First up
is a chop test.

23:20.983 --> 23:22.525
J.

23:22.568 --> 23:24.693
(Neilson)
Fellow bladesmiths,

23:24.737 --> 23:26.487
this is gonna test
the geometry of your blade

23:26.531 --> 23:28.155
and the strength of your blade,

23:28.199 --> 23:30.699
as well as the durability
of the cutting edge.

23:30.743 --> 23:32.993
Going to do 12 chops each.

23:33.037 --> 23:35.204
See how well
your knife performs.

23:35.248 --> 23:37.164
Matt, you're gonna be up first.

23:37.208 --> 23:38.958
(Matt)
I'm very nervous

23:39.001 --> 23:41.168
because I think my blade is
a little lighter.

23:41.212 --> 23:44.839
It's more of a slicing
and stabbing blade.

23:44.882 --> 23:53.222
♪ ♪

23:53.266 --> 23:56.267
It's not going as deeply
as I would like to see it go.

23:56.310 --> 23:58.477
Looks like the edge
held up well.

23:58.521 --> 24:01.439
I don't see any folds,
shiny spots.

24:03.484 --> 24:04.650
Good job.

24:04.694 --> 24:05.693
Thank you.

24:05.736 --> 24:07.695
Now going to measure
the depth

24:07.738 --> 24:09.071
of the deepest cut

24:09.115 --> 24:10.865
to see how far we got.

24:17.999 --> 24:19.582
You're just under
half an inch.

24:19.625 --> 24:22.877
Okay, that's great.

24:22.920 --> 24:24.336
(Neilson)
Peter, you're up next.

24:24.380 --> 24:25.921
(Pete)
This is a chopping blade.

24:25.965 --> 24:27.590
This is what I made it to do.

24:27.633 --> 24:31.802
So I think it's going to perform
very well on this test.

24:31.846 --> 24:34.805
[rock music]

24:34.849 --> 24:38.934
♪ ♪

24:43.816 --> 24:46.817
(Neilson)
It's held up well.

24:46.861 --> 24:48.861
No bends or warps.

24:48.905 --> 24:51.697
Handle feels pretty comfortable.

24:51.741 --> 24:53.491
Everything's firm.

24:53.534 --> 24:54.575
Thank you.

24:54.619 --> 24:56.118
Now we'll measure.

24:59.123 --> 25:02.750
Pete, looks like your blade
chopped a solid two inches.

25:02.793 --> 25:04.793
(Neilson)
Nice.

25:04.837 --> 25:06.295
You ready, Dave?

25:06.339 --> 25:07.254
Sure.

25:10.218 --> 25:14.178
(Dave)
So yeah, my handle's held
together with five-minute epoxy.

25:14.222 --> 25:16.722
I've got no problem with this
thing holding up pretty good.

25:29.111 --> 25:31.070
We're gonna do
the chop test now.

25:31.113 --> 25:32.404
(Neilson)
Are you ready, Dave?

25:32.448 --> 25:33.864
(Dave)
My handle's held together

25:33.908 --> 25:35.366
with five-minute epoxy.

25:35.409 --> 25:36.742
I've got no problem

25:36.786 --> 25:38.702
with this thing holding up
pretty good.

25:38.746 --> 25:41.789
[percussive music]

25:41.832 --> 25:49.588
♪ ♪

25:49.632 --> 25:51.257
(Neilson)
Edge held up well.

25:51.300 --> 25:52.800
I was worried about the handle.

25:52.843 --> 25:55.803
(Neilson)
It's a little bit rough.

25:55.846 --> 25:57.388
Nice job.

25:57.431 --> 25:58.722
Thank you.

25:58.766 --> 25:59.807
(Neilson)
Now we'll measure it.

25:59.850 --> 26:02.017
♪ ♪

26:02.061 --> 26:04.562
Dave, you're at
an inch and three quarters.

26:04.605 --> 26:06.272
Good.

26:06.315 --> 26:08.107
Next up, Doug Marcaida
will test

26:08.150 --> 26:09.984
how well your weapons
held an edge

26:10.027 --> 26:11.694
in a sharpness test.

26:11.737 --> 26:14.280
Matt, you're up first.

26:16.033 --> 26:17.533
For the test over here,

26:17.577 --> 26:19.994
I just want to see
if it held its cutting edge.

26:20.037 --> 26:23.872
If your blade held it's edge,
it will slice the tomatoes.

26:23.916 --> 26:26.333
If not, it won't break the skin.

26:26.377 --> 26:28.377
Okay.

26:28.421 --> 26:32.047
♪ ♪

26:32.091 --> 26:34.675
Matt, it cuts like a knife.

26:34.719 --> 26:35.759
That's good to hear.

26:35.803 --> 26:37.428
(Matt)
I'm relieved.

26:37.471 --> 26:39.555
I think I made up a little bit
on the sharpness test.

26:39.599 --> 26:41.724
Okay, Pete,
you're next.

26:41.767 --> 26:46.729
♪ ♪

26:46.772 --> 26:47.938
Very good.

26:47.982 --> 26:48.939
Thank you.

26:48.983 --> 26:50.399
You have a chopper here.

26:51.736 --> 26:54.236
(Marcaida)
Dave, you're next.

26:54.280 --> 26:58.574
♪ ♪

26:58.618 --> 27:00.451
It sliced through,

27:00.494 --> 27:03.370
but the feeling kind of
dragged me to the side.

27:03.414 --> 27:04.788
But just like
your fellow competitors,

27:04.832 --> 27:06.624
you all sliced through
all five tomatoes

27:06.667 --> 27:08.584
and passed this test
with flying colors.

27:08.628 --> 27:10.794
(Dave)
I can't control the outcome,

27:10.838 --> 27:13.672
but just that
not knowing factor

27:13.716 --> 27:16.634
is making me
a little bit nervous.

27:16.677 --> 27:20.387
♪ ♪

27:20.431 --> 27:23.265
If I had to pick one person
who I think is going home,

27:23.309 --> 27:25.059
I can't do it
at this point,

27:25.102 --> 27:28.145
because everybody's blade
did well in one test

27:28.189 --> 27:30.105
and not quite as well
in the other test.

27:30.149 --> 27:32.650
So it's really anybody's game
right now.

27:32.693 --> 27:35.277
♪ ♪

27:35.321 --> 27:36.737
(Willis)
It was a tough call,

27:36.781 --> 27:39.031
but the judges have made
their final decision.

27:39.075 --> 27:41.075
♪ ♪

27:41.118 --> 27:42.076
Matt,

27:42.119 --> 27:44.244
you didn't make the cut.

27:44.288 --> 27:46.121
Overall, I love your design.

27:46.165 --> 27:48.374
Your handle
I think is fantastic,

27:48.417 --> 27:52.127
but your blade's plunge lines
were still pretty off-center,

27:52.171 --> 27:54.380
but what really hurt you was
your blade just failed to chop

27:54.423 --> 27:56.548
as deeply as the others
in the wood chop test.

27:56.592 --> 27:57.925
Yep.

27:57.968 --> 27:59.385
(Baker)
That's why we got to let you go.

27:59.428 --> 28:00.636
I understand.

28:00.680 --> 28:02.513
Matt,

28:02.556 --> 28:04.556
please surrender
your weapon.

28:04.600 --> 28:06.517
(Matt)
I'm a little disappointed.

28:06.560 --> 28:08.268
I wanted to get into
the final round.

28:08.312 --> 28:09.478
Thank you, gentlemen.

28:09.522 --> 28:11.480
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

28:11.524 --> 28:14.024
(Matt)
Obviously, I could have done
things better,

28:14.068 --> 28:16.944
but that's the way
an artist life goes.

28:16.987 --> 28:18.904
You always know
you can do better.

28:18.948 --> 28:22.658
♪ ♪

28:22.702 --> 28:24.451
(Willis)
Pete, Dave,

28:24.495 --> 28:25.953
congratulations.

28:25.996 --> 28:29.707
You made it through
to the final round.

28:29.750 --> 28:31.625
To be crowned the
<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion,

28:31.669 --> 28:35.087
you must forge an iconic blade
from history.

28:35.131 --> 28:39.466
It's time to reveal
what that weapon will be.

28:39.510 --> 28:41.218
Holy crap.

28:41.262 --> 28:45.347
(Willis)
The crusader sword.

28:45.391 --> 28:48.016
Dating back to the Middle Ages,
the crusader sword was

28:48.060 --> 28:49.810
the European knights'
weapon of choice

28:49.854 --> 28:51.770
as they conquered the Holy Land.

28:51.814 --> 28:54.064
This single-handed,
medium length long sword

28:54.108 --> 28:57.109
also contained a double-edge
that tapered at the end,

28:57.153 --> 28:58.944
making it the ideal weapon
for piercing

28:58.988 --> 29:01.780
the emerging plate armor that
was found on most battlefields.

29:01.824 --> 29:04.992
The most famous crusader sword
was the legendary Excalibur

29:05.035 --> 29:06.744
wielded by King Arthur.

29:06.787 --> 29:09.288
A crusader sword was also
carried by the Knights Templar

29:09.331 --> 29:11.874
who were highlighted in films
like<i> Kingdom of Heaven</i>

29:11.917 --> 29:15.127
and<i> Indiana Jones</i>
<i> and the Last Crusade.</i>

29:15.171 --> 29:18.630
It must be an authentic,
fully-functioning version

29:18.674 --> 29:20.966
of that famous weapon.

29:21.010 --> 29:23.927
You will have just five days
to complete this challenge.

29:23.971 --> 29:27.639
(Dave)
I have never made
a crusader sword before.

29:27.683 --> 29:30.142
Having to make one
in only five days

29:30.186 --> 29:32.853
is gonna dinitely push me
to the max.

29:32.897 --> 29:35.522
Just to give you
the best possible chance,

29:35.566 --> 29:38.358
we are sending you back
to your home forge

29:38.402 --> 29:40.903
for this final round.

29:40.946 --> 29:43.781
In five days, you will return
to present your swords

29:43.824 --> 29:45.199
to the judges.

29:45.242 --> 29:47.618
They will be put through
a series of tests

29:47.661 --> 29:51.747
to judge its sharpness,
strength, and durability.

29:51.791 --> 29:54.041
(Willis)
Once these tests are completed,

29:54.084 --> 29:55.751
the judges will decide

29:55.795 --> 29:58.003
who will be crowned
the<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion

29:58.047 --> 30:02.257
and walk away with a check
for $10,000.

30:02.301 --> 30:03.300
Good luck.

30:03.344 --> 30:05.177
We will see you in five days.

30:08.307 --> 30:10.933
(Pete)
My forge at home is not at home.

30:10.976 --> 30:15.270
It's actually a shop that
I share with three other smiths.

30:15.314 --> 30:17.731
I'm feeling really excited
about this last challenge.

30:17.775 --> 30:21.109
The crusader sword is kind of
a broad category.

30:21.153 --> 30:25.072
I'm going much more
for flamboyance and style.

30:27.076 --> 30:30.619
My strategy here is to make
a Damascus billet,

30:30.663 --> 30:34.957
which is a laminated bar made up
of multiple layers of steel.

30:35.000 --> 30:38.252
And a jelly roll is a specific
pattern in Damascus

30:38.295 --> 30:40.879
where you actually roll
the steel up on itself,

30:40.923 --> 30:43.340
kind of like a cinnamon bun.

30:43.384 --> 30:45.342
Pretty tight.

30:45.386 --> 30:47.511
The jelly roll has reached
the point

30:47.555 --> 30:49.721
that I need to get it
into my hammer

30:49.765 --> 30:52.724
to squeeze it down on itself.

30:57.523 --> 31:00.023
(Dave)
My experience in crusader swords

31:00.067 --> 31:03.527
is nonexistent.

31:03.571 --> 31:07.114
I'm gonna stick with what
history has shown

31:07.157 --> 31:09.575
and that's with simplicity.

31:09.618 --> 31:13.996
I want to make sure that this is
going to perform without fail.

31:14.039 --> 31:16.915
Everything's good there.

31:19.879 --> 31:22.462
(Pete)
Looks pretty clean
along the edges now.

31:22.506 --> 31:26.842
So we're gonna proceed
to forging this out.

31:26.886 --> 31:29.636
[metal clanging]

31:29.680 --> 31:31.555
Okay.

31:31.599 --> 31:34.641
I got plenty of width and
I am struggling for length.

31:34.685 --> 31:38.145
And if I can't get this last
little bit of length,

31:38.188 --> 31:40.981
then I'm either going to have to
risk it with the judges

31:41.025 --> 31:42.357
or start from scratch.

31:42.401 --> 31:43.817
[metal clanging]

31:45.279 --> 31:46.695
(Dave)
Forges are generally designed

31:46.739 --> 31:49.156
for certain particular
applications.

31:49.199 --> 31:52.784
This one is not meant
for swords.

31:52.828 --> 31:56.038
Having a blade so long
makes it very difficult

31:56.081 --> 31:58.916
to get it to evenly heat.

31:58.959 --> 32:00.626
I'm gonna put the blade
in the oil.

32:00.669 --> 32:03.462
I'm gonna pull it out
just enough for it to flash.

32:03.505 --> 32:07.925
♪ ♪

32:07.968 --> 32:09.885
[bleep].

32:09.929 --> 32:13.305
Any time that thing got hot
in the forge,

32:13.349 --> 32:14.431
it would warp.

32:14.475 --> 32:18.810
I could literally watch it bend.

32:18.854 --> 32:23.774
This is called a three-pin
straightening method.

32:23.817 --> 32:25.817
I'm gonna either straighten
this blade

32:25.861 --> 32:29.112
or I'm gonna snap it.

32:29.156 --> 32:31.865
I really don't like
doing this.

32:33.744 --> 32:35.827
[heavy rock music]

32:35.871 --> 32:39.081
(Pete)
I'm really happy with how
the Damascus pattern came out.

32:39.124 --> 32:42.542
And now I've decided
that I want a small spacer

32:42.586 --> 32:44.044
between the leather-wrapped
handle

32:44.088 --> 32:45.504
and the guard.

32:45.547 --> 32:47.798
So I've carved
a small piece of antler

32:47.841 --> 32:50.968
just to make a nice,
decorative transition piece.

32:51.011 --> 32:52.636
[British accent]
That's nice and tight.

32:52.680 --> 32:55.305
I feel great
about what I've made,

32:55.349 --> 32:56.890
and if Dave beats it,

32:56.934 --> 32:59.351
that means he's brought
something incredible.

32:59.395 --> 33:01.061
♪ ♪

33:01.105 --> 33:02.479
(Dave)
So luckily,

33:02.523 --> 33:03.772
the blade didn't break
in the vice.

33:03.816 --> 33:05.357
I was able to fix the warp.

33:05.401 --> 33:06.984
Now I got to get this sword
finished.

33:07.027 --> 33:08.485
The handle is walnut

33:08.529 --> 33:12.030
and my overlay
is a leather band.

33:12.074 --> 33:14.992
I decided to put inside
the handle a riser

33:15.035 --> 33:16.118
underneath the leather.

33:16.161 --> 33:17.911
It's pleasing to the eye

33:17.955 --> 33:21.248
and it helps with the grip.

33:21.291 --> 33:23.125
Confidence level's pretty high.

33:23.168 --> 33:26.378
I'm really pleased
with the outcome of this.

33:26.422 --> 33:29.089
I've got a great chance at this
in the end with the judges.

33:29.133 --> 33:31.633
♪ ♪

33:41.854 --> 33:44.813
[tense music]

33:44.857 --> 33:47.357
♪ ♪

33:47.401 --> 33:50.068
Bladesmiths, welcome back.

33:50.112 --> 33:53.155
For the types of tests that we
wanted to do with your weapons,

33:53.198 --> 33:55.449
we had to change locations
from the forge

33:55.492 --> 33:59.286
to a location that provides a
little bit more maneuverability.

33:59.329 --> 34:00.996
Yeah.

34:01.040 --> 34:03.331
Pete, can you tell us
a little bit about your sword?

34:03.375 --> 34:05.042
(Pete)
It's a laminated blade,

34:05.085 --> 34:07.669
which adds a level of detail

34:07.713 --> 34:10.547
that you don't see much
in swords these days.

34:10.591 --> 34:12.758
I think it's gonna
kick butt.

34:12.801 --> 34:14.926
Dave, how was your five days?

34:14.970 --> 34:16.261
It was great.

34:16.305 --> 34:17.804
(Dave)
I kept it simple.

34:17.848 --> 34:22.225
I decided to stick with
a steel that I know, 5160.

34:22.269 --> 34:24.352
The handle itself is walnut

34:24.396 --> 34:27.314
and my overlay is a leather band

34:27.357 --> 34:31.735
and then on top of that
is a very thin deerskin hide.

34:31.779 --> 34:33.236
(Willis)
Great.

34:33.280 --> 34:34.237
Now it's time to find out
whether or not

34:34.281 --> 34:35.572
they're works of art

34:35.616 --> 34:38.450
or deadly weapons of war.

34:38.494 --> 34:41.661
While the crusader sword was
quite powerful and effective

34:41.705 --> 34:43.955
on foot
in sword-to-sword combat,

34:43.999 --> 34:45.499
there was a method of delivery

34:45.542 --> 34:48.293
that made it
even more destructive:

34:48.337 --> 34:50.962
from horseback.

34:51.006 --> 34:54.508
♪ ♪

34:54.551 --> 34:57.052
That rider is gonna use
your weapons

34:57.096 --> 34:59.387
to attack that
ballistics gel torso

34:59.431 --> 35:03.600
that's wearing a great helm,
gorget, and tunic.

35:03.644 --> 35:06.269
Before we put your swords
through the kill test,

35:06.313 --> 35:08.313
we first want to see
if they can not break

35:08.357 --> 35:11.399
when subjected to a blow
delivered from on top of a horse

35:11.443 --> 35:12.901
at full gallop.

35:12.945 --> 35:14.152
Okay.

35:14.196 --> 35:15.737
(Willis)
I suggest we get out of the way.

35:15.781 --> 35:16.863
(Pete)
I'm very nervous.

35:16.907 --> 35:18.990
Full gallop on horseback,

35:19.034 --> 35:20.992
that's a lot of power
to put into a sword.

35:21.036 --> 35:22.869
(Willis)
Dave, you're up first.

35:22.913 --> 35:23.995
Are you ready?

35:24.039 --> 35:25.122
I ain't gonna get
any readier.

35:25.165 --> 35:28.959
Three, two, one.
Engage.

35:29.002 --> 35:32.712
♪ ♪

35:32.756 --> 35:35.090
[Dave chuckles]

35:35.134 --> 35:36.883
Nice hit.

35:36.927 --> 35:40.220
So seeing the rider go up
against this dummy with my sword

35:40.264 --> 35:42.222
and it did not break on impact,

35:42.266 --> 35:44.724
that is absolutely awesome.

35:44.768 --> 35:46.017
(Willis)
Pete, your sword's up next.

35:46.061 --> 35:47.269
Let's see some blood.

35:47.312 --> 35:52.149
♪ ♪

35:52.192 --> 35:55.569
I feel great
that my sword held up well,

35:55.612 --> 35:58.822
but it didn't cut through
the cloth armor.

35:58.866 --> 36:00.198
(Willis)
To assess the damage

36:00.242 --> 36:02.325
and perform the kill test,

36:02.369 --> 36:05.162
I'm gonna hand you over
to Doug.

36:06.456 --> 36:08.248
(Marcaida)
Okay, Dave.

36:12.171 --> 36:14.379
It's got some weight to it.

36:14.423 --> 36:17.632
A crusader sword should feel
a bit heavy in the hand.

36:17.676 --> 36:19.676
Slashing feels good.

36:22.097 --> 36:23.763
Let's see if it will cut.

36:23.807 --> 36:25.015
Okay.

36:25.058 --> 36:28.018
[percussive music]

36:28.061 --> 36:29.269
♪ ♪

36:29.313 --> 36:32.230
[gel squishing]

36:40.115 --> 36:41.531
(Pete)
Oh.

36:41.575 --> 36:43.617
You can see it points
like a spear.

36:43.660 --> 36:46.578
Beautiful thrusting capability.

36:46.622 --> 36:47.954
It's a killer.

36:47.998 --> 36:49.623
(Dave)
I had a lot of anxiety,

36:49.666 --> 36:52.375
but I did really good.

36:52.419 --> 36:54.586
At this point, I'm ecstatic.

36:54.630 --> 36:56.254
(Marcaida)
Pete.

36:56.298 --> 36:58.590
♪ ♪

36:58.634 --> 37:01.801
So now testing for the thrusting
with length.

37:01.845 --> 37:04.846
It's got a lot
of weight to it.

37:04.890 --> 37:06.431
♪ ♪

37:06.475 --> 37:08.141
Let's see what it's gonna do
on a kill test.

37:08.185 --> 37:10.227
Let's see.

37:10.270 --> 37:12.103
[tense music]

37:12.147 --> 37:15.106
[gel squishing]

37:15.150 --> 37:19.194
♪ ♪

37:19.238 --> 37:22.155
[Dave chuckles]

37:23.992 --> 37:27.452
It will kill.

37:27.496 --> 37:28.536
All right, gentlemen,

37:28.580 --> 37:30.455
that concludes the kill test.

37:30.499 --> 37:32.040
Now we're gonna head back
to the forge

37:32.084 --> 37:34.793
where we are going to perform
the strength test.

37:34.836 --> 37:40.924
♪ ♪

37:40.968 --> 37:42.592
(Willis)
Welcome back.

37:42.636 --> 37:45.804
Looks like your blades are
standing up to our tests,

37:45.847 --> 37:47.138
but we have one left.

37:47.182 --> 37:49.391
We have the strength test.

37:49.434 --> 37:51.017
Okay.

37:51.061 --> 37:52.686
(Willis) Now I'm gonna
turn you over to Dave,

37:52.729 --> 37:55.730
who's an expert in European
sword design and usage.

37:55.774 --> 37:57.357
(Pete)
So we're done with the kill test

37:57.401 --> 37:58.692
at the arena.

37:58.735 --> 38:00.819
We're neck and neck
on performance.

38:00.862 --> 38:02.237
Gentlemen,

38:02.281 --> 38:06.116
a sword in combat went through
extreme stresses.

38:06.159 --> 38:08.952
So to test this,
I'm gonna take five blows

38:08.996 --> 38:10.704
against these femurs

38:10.747 --> 38:11.997
to see how far through
we can get

38:12.040 --> 38:12.998
with each of your weapons.

38:13.041 --> 38:14.291
Okay.

38:14.334 --> 38:16.293
- Pete, you ready?
- I'm ready.

38:16.336 --> 38:17.419
(Baker)
All right.

38:17.462 --> 38:18.920
(Pete)
As soon as I see

38:18.964 --> 38:22.048
that they're going to be
chopping cow bones,

38:22.092 --> 38:24.718
that makes me really nervous.

38:24.761 --> 38:26.303
♪ ♪

38:33.812 --> 38:36.146
Gentlemen,
I'm gonna take five blows

38:36.189 --> 38:37.564
against these femurs

38:37.607 --> 38:38.815
to see how far through
we can get

38:38.859 --> 38:41.234
with each of your weapons.

38:41.278 --> 38:42.777
Pete, you ready?

38:42.821 --> 38:44.279
- I'm ready.
- All right.

38:44.323 --> 38:46.489
(Pete)
This is a very hard substance.

38:46.533 --> 38:48.450
They're going to be
hitting it hard.

38:48.493 --> 38:50.618
That makes me really nervous.

38:50.662 --> 38:53.621
[dramatic music]

38:53.665 --> 39:01.963
♪ ♪

39:02.007 --> 39:03.381
(Pete)
Wow.

39:05.093 --> 39:07.093
[bleep].

39:09.765 --> 39:13.350
While I was chopping,
this ring up here,

39:13.393 --> 39:14.351
pretty rough on the hand.

39:14.394 --> 39:16.061
Okay.

39:16.104 --> 39:17.687
I'm just happy that my sword
is still in one piece

39:17.731 --> 39:19.147
at the end of this.

39:19.191 --> 39:20.357
[chuckles]

39:20.400 --> 39:22.650
Got about halfway through
that bone.

39:22.694 --> 39:25.653
Just blowing pieces
off of it.

39:25.697 --> 39:29.657
And still has an edge.

39:29.701 --> 39:30.658
Nice job.

39:30.702 --> 39:32.202
Thank you.

39:32.245 --> 39:33.453
(Baker)
Dave, you're up next.

39:33.497 --> 39:34.704
You ready?

39:34.748 --> 39:36.039
Sure.

39:36.083 --> 39:37.540
[Baker chuckles]

39:37.584 --> 39:39.167
I'm seeing these femur bones,

39:39.211 --> 39:42.212
I'm getting ready
to almost throw up.

39:42.255 --> 39:44.631
I don't want to see this
destroyed.

39:44.674 --> 39:47.634
[heavy rock music]

39:47.677 --> 39:55.600
♪ ♪

40:00.399 --> 40:02.273
[quietly]
Bent.

40:03.985 --> 40:05.693
[sighs]

40:05.737 --> 40:08.363
Lot of stress in that blade.

40:08.407 --> 40:09.656
No kidding.

40:09.699 --> 40:11.533
You see the edge
folded over.

40:11.576 --> 40:13.118
Yeah.

40:13.161 --> 40:15.203
Sort of bent right around
that point of impact

40:15.247 --> 40:16.579
right there.

40:16.623 --> 40:20.542
You can see we chopped
right through this bone.

40:20.585 --> 40:22.710
About three blows
to crack that open.

40:22.754 --> 40:26.381
(Dave)
Watching Dave work on those
bones with my sword

40:26.425 --> 40:29.551
is the absolute most
nerve-racking,

40:29.594 --> 40:32.720
stomach-twisting experience

40:32.764 --> 40:34.681
that I've ever had
as a knife maker.

40:36.435 --> 40:38.184
Well done.

40:38.228 --> 40:40.645
Until the judges say
one way or the other,

40:40.689 --> 40:41.980
I'm still--

40:42.023 --> 40:43.648
I'm still nervous.

40:45.485 --> 40:51.739
♪ ♪

40:51.783 --> 40:54.159
You've both been
outstanding competitors

40:54.202 --> 40:57.495
through three rounds
of competition,

40:57.539 --> 41:01.166
but there can only be one

41:01.209 --> 41:03.835
<i> Forged in Fire</i> champion.

41:03.879 --> 41:04.961
(Willis)
J.

41:05.005 --> 41:06.254
Well, Pete,

41:06.298 --> 41:08.298
that Damascus blade
was beautiful.

41:08.341 --> 41:11.009
I mean, getting all those welds
folded together,

41:11.052 --> 41:12.302
grinding that all evenly,

41:12.345 --> 41:13.386
heat-treating it
the way you did,

41:13.430 --> 41:14.846
it stood up to all the tests.

41:14.890 --> 41:18.099
You did a wonderful job
on that piece of steel.

41:18.143 --> 41:19.476
I had a couple of issues

41:19.519 --> 41:20.810
with the way your handle
was put together

41:20.854 --> 41:22.395
with that spacer.

41:22.439 --> 41:26.107
The spacer really started
chewing into my hand.

41:26.151 --> 41:29.569
I just couldn't get a good grip
up around the top of the sword.

41:29.613 --> 41:30.820
(Baker)
That's an issue.

41:30.864 --> 41:31.988
(Willis)
Comments for Dave?

41:32.032 --> 41:33.448
(Neilson)
Oh, Dave,

41:33.492 --> 41:35.366
even though the overall look
of your sword

41:35.410 --> 41:37.702
and the design of your handle
was very appealing,

41:37.746 --> 41:39.787
obviously, it was
a heat treatment issue.

41:39.831 --> 41:42.165
During the tests,
your blade folded over

41:42.209 --> 41:44.751
and that really bit you
in the testing.

41:44.794 --> 41:46.878
Dave, I love the design
of your blade.

41:46.922 --> 41:48.755
Very clean lines.

41:48.798 --> 41:51.090
Your handle felt very good
in the hand.

41:51.134 --> 41:52.926
It's sharp.
It thrust well.

41:52.969 --> 41:57.180
But in the end, it failed when
we started slicing the bones.

41:57.224 --> 42:00.183
[upbeat percussive music]

42:00.227 --> 42:03.228
♪ ♪

42:03.271 --> 42:07.106
(Willis)
Pete,

42:07.150 --> 42:09.275
you are the<i> Forged in Fire</i>
champion.

42:09.319 --> 42:11.861
Congratulations.

42:11.905 --> 42:13.154
(Baker)
Dave,

42:13.198 --> 42:15.365
your sword felt great
in the hand,

42:15.408 --> 42:18.034
but when I used it
on those bones,

42:18.078 --> 42:20.078
boy, it just bent
right over the top

42:20.121 --> 42:22.622
and the heat treat issue
like that,

42:22.666 --> 42:25.166
we just can't let that through.

42:25.210 --> 42:28.503
Dave,
you did an outstanding job.

42:28.547 --> 42:30.171
Please surrender your weapon.

42:30.215 --> 42:32.882
(Dave)
The judges' decision was
what it was.

42:32.926 --> 42:36.010
If I can't change it,
then why worry about it?

42:36.054 --> 42:39.430
I had a tremendous time
doing this.

42:39.474 --> 42:40.515
It was an education,

42:40.559 --> 42:42.183
a wonderful experience,

42:42.227 --> 42:44.060
and definitely one
that I'm never gonna forget.

42:44.104 --> 42:47.730
[heavy rock music]

42:47.774 --> 42:49.023
Pete, congratulations.

42:49.067 --> 42:51.276
You're receiving a check
for $10,000.

42:51.319 --> 42:52.860
That's pretty nice.

42:52.904 --> 42:54.153
How do you feel?

42:54.197 --> 42:55.822
I feel great.
I feel really good.

42:55.865 --> 42:57.615
(Pete)
I think my wife,

42:57.659 --> 43:00.451
when we get to Hawaii,
we're gonna lie back and relax.

43:00.495 --> 43:03.246
She's had to put up
with me being gone for this.

43:03.290 --> 43:04.581
She deserves it.

43:04.624 --> 43:09.168
♪ ♪
